AB  - We consider the 12-month moving average aggregate default rate of S&P-rated US-bonds. We estimate the conditional probability distribution of this default rate as a function of a weighted average bond rating, a lagged default rate and a preliminary predictor that is based on lagged new issuance. Our modeling approach is asymptotically optimal for an expected utility maximizing investor. The resulting conditional probability density is consistent with our intuition. We measure the model’s performance by the out-of-sample expected utility. According to this measure, our model clearly outperforms a simple regression model, a regression model with ARMA error terms and a Poisson model.
